# Blog Article Creation

When the user asks to "create an article" (or similar), follow this format without asking for structural details.

## Frontmatter Template

```yaml
---
title: 'Article Title Here'
description: 'Single-quoted description for SEO and social cards.'
published: true
tags: 'tag1, tag2, tag3'
---
```

- `title`, `description` (single-quoted) – quote both to avoid YAML parsing failures with special chars (e.g. `:`, `&`, `–`, `'`)
- `published: true`
- `tags: 'tag1, tag2, tag3'` (max 4, alphanumeric only, no hyphens—use `secretsmanager` not `secrets-manager`, comma-separated)
- Omit `id` and `date` for new articles (auto-generated by dev.to on publish)

## Article Structure

1. `## Title` (H2, matches frontmatter title) + intro paragraph
2. `---` horizontal rule between sections
3. `### 1. Overview` – bullet list of what the guide does (and common causes if troubleshooting)
4. `### 2. Prerequisites` – bullet list of requirements
5. `### 3.` through `### N.` – step-by-step sections with subsections (`####`) as needed
6. `### N. Summary: Copy-Paste` – copy-paste ready commands
7. `### N+1. Troubleshooting` – issue/solution pairs
8. `### N+2. References` – links to docs, related articles

## Naming

- Before creating, list `articles/art*.md` and pick the next sequential number (e.g. highest art0117 → use art0118)
- File path: `articles/art0XXX.md`

## dev.to Rules

- No H1 (`#`) in body; dev.to uses the title as H1. Start with `##`
- Fenced code blocks must specify language (`bash`, `yaml`, `text`, etc.)
- No bare URLs; use `[text](url)`
- No inline HTML; use markdown

## Cross-References

When referencing another article, use `[Title](https://dev.to/jajera/slug)`. Update the slug after publish if needed.
